The 2001 Profitability Survey was based on the assumption that the borderline and the section leading through the Bohemian Central Mountains would simultaneously go under traffic.
At the time of the examination, it was obvious that the section through the Bohemian Central Mountains would not be opened at the original date.
This reduces the above EIRR values.
At 31.12.2005, the cost of both sections was €897 million, excluding VAT, and thus 27.4% higher than in the 2001 profitability assessment.
There is also a risk that section 0805 will get another more elaborate inistray, which would affect the project's cost-effectiveness.
The profitability assessment showed that the construction of both sections of the motorway is socially justified with a daily traffic volume of at least 18 000 motor vehicles per day in 2010. The 2008 forecast had predicted 22 940 cars per day.
However, a study on diversions as an alternative to the missing section by the Bohemian Central Mountains assumes a traffic volume of 12 600 to 13 750 vehicles per day in 2007. The project is then below the economic limit.
A higher volume of traffic on the routes intended to replace the missing section with the Bohemian Central Mountains is likely to result in congestion and thus increased external costs which were not taken into account in the original profitability investigation.
The mentioned reduction in revenue and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR for building the border section of the D 8 will not be achieved.
Construction of the border section of the D 8 is therefore uneconomic.
There were also increases in costs in the construction of the A 17 as in the construction of the two above. Sections of the D 8.
As part of the general economic assessment for the 1992 Federal Transport Plan, the Federal Ministry of Transport assumed investment costs of approximately €320 million.
Thus, it established a benefit/cost ratio of 4.6.
Meanwhile, costs increased to around €670 million and the benefit/cost ratio decreased by more than half.
Regardless of the parallel tests with the NKÚ in 2003 to 2005, the BRH had examined the cost-effectiveness of the planning and construction of Highway A 17.
In doing so, he noted that the authority responsible for the approval called for an unnecessary runway tunnel for the third section of A 17.
During the course of the test, the BRH succeeded in convincing the city and road construction administration of the over-fluid of the runway tunnel.
As a result, €10 million in construction costs and €150 000 in annual operating costs could be avoided.
When testing the first section of the A 17, the BRH found that the construction measure was inadequate.
The following example makes this clear:
During the planning phase, the road construction administration waived a state recording of the field at the surface of the Dölzschener Wand, as this was difficult to access.
It was not until the tunnel drive reached the wall that it retrieved this.
In doing so, it was revealed that the rock was more weathered than was assumed during the tender.
Elaborate measures such as anchorages, injections and stone impact protection networks for around €3.3 million were needed.
The road construction administration did not only bear the cost of additional, already required, eistings such as securing the Dölzschener wall, but also of those that would not have been necessary for proper construction preparation at all.
This includes expenditure due to disturbed construction processes (€3.2 million), additional preparation of the advance team (€0.5 million) and increased wages and material prices due to the extension of the construction time (€7 million).
This additional expenditure of around €10.7 million is no lasting added value.
The BRH took these and further measures to call on the Federal Ministry to better carry out the technical supervision of major road construction measures in place.
In this context, it should push for road construction administrations to introduce quality assurance systems.
Benefits of cooperation for BRH and NKÚ Cooperation met the expectations of both accounting offices.
The BRH obtained insights into the planning, procurement and execution of the construction of the border bridge.
Both accounting offices developed a data inventory at bridge and tunnel prices, which will be helpful in future audits.
The NKÚ noted that the main structural parameters for bridges, tunnels and construction sites of D 8 are not different from those of A 17.
The auditors of both audit firms involved in the cooperation gathered valuable experiences that will be useful in future audits.
